@node Building with Nix
@section Building with Nix

Twist builds packages with the @uref{https://nixos.org/, Nix} package manager, a purely functional package manager for Linux and macOS@.
Rather than running a build process inside a running session of Emacs, it builds packages in a sandboxed Nix session.
This ensures that your entire configuration is reproducible.

Twist avoids systems programming in Emacs Lisp, which is hard to get right.
Nix handles most of the heavy lifting in package management, which makes the build process reliable and performant.

@node Lock individual packages
@section Lock individual packages

Twist lets you lock individual package versions.
This is different from @samp{emacsWithPackages} in Nixpkgs, which basically updates all packages to the latest version at once.
In Twist, you can select which packages to update, and the remaining packages won't be updated, even if their upstream repositories have newer revisions.
This is a recommended practice for security.

The format of a lock file is @samp{flake.nix} + @samp{flake.lock}, so you can use Nix to update packages.
You don't need a separate command for maintenance.

@node Support various package repositories
@section Support various package repositories

Twist can build most Emacs Lisp packages available from Git repositories.
It is capable of building quite a few packages on GNU/NonGNU ELPA and MELPA from sources.
Some packages from GNU ELPA cannot be built from sources, but Twist can also take advantage of pre-built package archives and Emacsmirror.

For Core ELPA packages, it can build them from a specific revision of the source repository of GNU Emacs.

With Twist, it is also easy to add packages from the wild.
Perhaps this is the biggest advantage of Twist over @samp{emacsWithPackages}.
Rather than writing a Nix expression (with a revision hash and checksum) for every package you want to add, you can simply create a MELPA recipe and run a lock command.
Those custom packages are tracked in @samp{flake.lock}, so it is also easy to update them.

@node Pure builds vs impure builds
@section Pure builds vs. impure builds

With Twist, there is a clear distinction between pure and impure builds of configuration.
If there is any package that is not tracked in the lock file, building the configuration will be impure.
Otherwise, all packages are locked, and the build is pure.
Impure build requires @samp{--impure} flag of Nix.
It still allows impure builds, for ease of development, but you will know whether your configuration will be reproducible on other machines.

@node Build subset profiles with minimal extra time
@section Build subset profiles with minimal extra time

Typical package managers for Emacs store packages in @samp{user-emacs-directory}.
If the user has multiple configuration profiles using a tool like @uref{https://github.com/plexus/chemacs2, chemacs2}, the installation time will be approximately proportional to the number of profiles.

On the contrary, Twist is based on Nix, so it stores all sources and artifacts in the centralized Nix store.
If the user has multiple configuration profiles with the same revision set of packages, it requires almost no extra time for installing multiple profiles.
The total time will be almost the same as the build time for their master profile.
This saves your time, if you have such use cases.

@uref{https://github.com/emacs-twist/org-babel, org-babel} library for Nix allows you to define subprofiles from a single Org file according to tags.

@node nix eval-friendly APIs
@section nix eval-friendly APIs

Twist exposes an API that is accessible via @samp{nix eval} command.
You can inspect metadata of a specific package or all packages without running the configuration.
This shouldn't be necessary, but it helps troubleshooting once the build process fails.
It is also possible to export an entire package set to JSON, which can be used to script around your configuration.

@node Creating a self-contained environment with required executables
@section Creating a self-contained environment with required executables

Twist provides an option for feeding packages from Nixpkgs to @samp{exec-path} of Emacs.
This is equivalent to @samp{use-package-ensure-system-package}, but it doesn't rely on imperative usage of a package manager.

@node Almost no runtime
@section Almost no runtime

Twist builds packages outside of a live Emacs session, and it requires no runtime, except for loading pre-generated autoloads.
The startup time of Twist-based Emacs is as fast as that of @samp{package.el}, or maybe even slightly faster.

@node System requirements
@chapter System requirements

Twist depends on the Nix package manager.
Nix is currently supported on Linux and macOS@.
For details, refer to the manual of Nix: @uref{https://nixos.org/manual/nix/stable/installation/supported-platforms.html}

Also, the Nix package manager on your system must be version 2.4 or later.
To check the version of Nix, run the following command on terminal:

@example
nix --version
@end example

The command should print an output as follows:

@example
nix (Nix) 2.8.0pre20220411_f7276bc
@end example

If you don't have Nix, you can download it from here: @uref{https://nixos.org/download.html}

@node Installation
@chapter Installation

Before you use Twist on your machine, you may need an additional configuration.

@menu
* Turn on Nix flakes::
* Add an access token to GitHub::
@end menu

@node Turn on Nix flakes
@section Turn on Nix flakes

Twist is designed for use in a Nix flake.
Flakes are an experimental feature of Nix, and may be turned off by default depending on your Nix version.

To turn on the feature, follow the instruction in the following article: @uref{https://nixos.wiki/wiki/Flakes#Installing_flakes}

@node Add an access token to GitHub
@section Add an access token to GitHub

Twist is a source-based build machinery.
It fetches package sources from upstream repositories with Nix.
As most Emacs Lisp packages are hosted on @uref{https://github.com/, GitHub} nowadays, and GitHub imposes a rather strict rate limit (60 per hour) on API access, you are likely to be blocked from @samp{api.github.com} when you use Twist.

To mitigate this issue, you can expand the rate limit by using authorized access to GitHub.
This will increase the rate limit to 5000 per hour, which is sufficient for normal use.

To enable authorized access to GitHub, you have to generate an access token on GitHub and add it to your @samp{nix.conf}.
You need a GitHub account.

@enumerate
@item
Log in to your GitHub account, go to @uref{https://github.com/settings/apps, Developer Settings}, and visit @emph{Personal access tokens}.
@item
Press @emph{Generate new token} button.
@item
Set a note and expiration. Select @samp{repo:status} and @samp{public_repo}, and press @emph{Generate token} button.
@item
Copy the token and add it to your @samp{nix.conf}.
@end enumerate

When you finish these steps, your @samp{nix.conf} should contain a line as follows:

@example
access-tokens = github.com=XXXXXX
@end example

For details on rate limiting on GitHub, refer to the following section in the GitHub Docs:
@uref{https://docs.github.com/en/rest/overview/resources-in-the-rest-api#rate-limiting}

For details on scopes, refer to the following article in the GitHub Docs: @uref{https://docs.github.com/en/developers/apps/building-oauth-apps/scopes-for-oauth-apps}

