@node Initializing from a template
@section Initializing from a template

To create a new configuration from scratch, you can use a template.
First, create an empty directory.
Then, run the following command in the directory:

@example
nix flake init -t github:emacs-twist/twist.nix
@end example

The template creates the following files:

@itemize
@item
@samp{flake.nix} — the Nix flake with all inputs (nixpkgs, twist, MELPA, GNU ELPA, NonGNU ELPA, Emacsmirror) and the call to @samp{twist.lib.makeEnv}.
@item
@samp{init.el} — a starter init file using @samp{use-package}.  Add @samp{use-package} blocks with @samp{:ensure t} here.
@item
@samp{early-init.el} — sets @samp{package-enable-at-startup} to @samp{nil} so that @samp{package.el} does not run at startup.
@item
@samp{lock/} — an empty lock directory (contains @samp{.gitkeep}) where Twist will write @samp{flake.nix}, @samp{flake.lock}, and @samp{archive.lock}.
@item
@samp{README.md} — quick-start instructions.
@end itemize

Now you can work on your configuration by adding @samp{use-package} blocks to @samp{init.el}.

Twist also provides some extra flexibility on configuration:

@itemize
@item
Manage your configuration in an Org file
@item
Use an alternative utility other than @samp{use-package}, like @samp{setup.el}
@end itemize

Otherwise, you can skip the following subsections to start developing your configuration.

@node Manual creation of a project boilerplate
@section Manual creation of a project boilerplate

Alternatively, if you already have an Emacs configuration built with Nix, you can migrate your configuration to Twist by tweaking your configuration.

This subsection assumes you have a flake for your Emacs configuration.

@menu
* Create flake.nix: Create flakenix. 
* Add flake inputs::
* Create a lock directory::
* Define flake outputs::
@end menu

@node Create flakenix
@subsection Create flake.nix

You must track your configuration in a Git repository, and the root directory of the repository must contain @samp{flake.nix}.
It must follow the format of @uref{https://nixos.wiki/wiki/Flakes, Nix flakes} as recognized by Nix.
You can run the following command to create a @samp{flake.nix}:

@example
nix flake init
@end example

@node Add flake inputs
@subsection Add flake inputs

To use Twist, you have to add @samp{github:emacs-twist/twist.nix} to the inputs:

@example
inputs.twist.url = "github:emacs-twist/twist.nix";
@end example

You will also need to add flake inputs for the registries you use.
See @ref{Registry Configuration} for details.

@node Create a lock directory
@subsection Create a lock directory

You have to create a directory for lock files.
The directory can be anywhere inside the repository, but not the root directory of the repository.

For example, if the directory is named @samp{lock}, you can use the following commands:

@example
mkdir -p lock
touch lock/.gitkeep
git add lock/.gitkeep
@end example

Note that the directory must not be empty.
It must be considered non-empty by Nix, so you have to create an empty file (e.g. @samp{.gitkeep}) in the directory and add it to the Git index.

@node Define flake outputs
@subsection Define flake outputs

A typical @samp{flake.nix} looks like the following.
It uses @samp{nixpkgs.lib.genAttrs} together with the @samp{nix-systems/default} helper to support multiple systems:

@example
@{
  inputs = @{
    nixpkgs.url = "github:NixOS/nixpkgs/nixos-unstable";
    systems.url = "github:nix-systems/default";
    twist.url = "github:emacs-twist/twist.nix";
    # ... registry inputs (melpa, gnu-elpa, etc.) ...
  @};

  outputs = @{ nixpkgs, systems, twist, ... @} @@ inputs:
    let
      eachSystem = f:
        nixpkgs.lib.genAttrs (import systems)
          (system: f (import nixpkgs @{ inherit system; @}));

      inherit (twist.lib) makeEnv;

      emacsConfig = pkgs: makeEnv @{
        inherit pkgs;
        # ... configuration options ...
      @};
    in @{
      packages = eachSystem (pkgs: rec @{
        emacs = emacsConfig pkgs;
        default = emacs;
      @});

      apps = eachSystem (pkgs:
        (emacsConfig pkgs).makeApps @{ lockDirName = "lock"; @}
      );
    @};
@}
@end example

It is also possible to use other libraries such as @uref{https://github.com/numtide/flake-utils, flake-utils} for the boilerplate.
If you want to track the Emacs configuration in the same repository as a NixOS/home-manager configuration, @uref{https://github.com/gytis-ivaskevicius/flake-utils-plus, flake-utils-plus} is recommended, but it is not described in this manual.

@enumerate
@item
@anchor{Define a package}Define a package


The configuration is built using @samp{twist.lib.makeEnv}:

@example
inherit (twist.lib) makeEnv;

emacsConfig = pkgs: makeEnv @{
  inherit pkgs;
  emacsPackage = pkgs.emacs;

  # The path to the lock directory
  lockDir = ./lock;

  # Your Emacs initialization file(s)
  initFiles = [ ./init.el ];

  # Registries (package-source metadata)
  registries = [ ... ];
@};
@end example

The result is a scope (an attribute set that is also a derivation), so you can add it to the flake outputs:

@example
packages = eachSystem (pkgs: rec @{
  emacs = emacsConfig pkgs;
  default = emacs;
@});
@end example

@item
@anchor{Derive apps for administration}Derive apps for administration


You will also need apps to lock and update packages.
You can add these outputs as follows:

@example
apps = eachSystem (pkgs:
  (emacsConfig pkgs).makeApps @{ lockDirName = "lock"; @}
);
@end example

You have to set @samp{lockDirName} to the path to the lock directory as a string.
@samp{makeApps} exposes two apps:

@itemize
@item
@samp{nix run .#lock} — regenerates @samp{lock/flake.nix} and @samp{lock/archive.lock}, then runs @samp{nix flake lock} to update @samp{lock/flake.lock}.
@item
@samp{nix run .#update} — refreshes the archive lock (@samp{lock/archive.lock}) with latest packages from ELPA package archives.
@end itemize
@end enumerate

