@node Registry Configuration
@section Registry Configuration

@emph{Registries} are repositories from which Twist can discover information on Emacs Lisp packages.

In GNU Emacs, the user can install packages from package archives such as GNU ELPA, NonGNU ELPA, and MELPA@.
Those archives serve pre-built files and tarballs which can be installed using @samp{package.el}.

While Twist supports package archives, it is primarily intended for building packages from sources.
Twist somehow needs to discover the source repositories of packages the user wants to install, and those meta-repositories are called registries.

Registries are passed to @samp{twist.lib.makeEnv} as the @samp{registries} argument — a list of attribute sets, each describing one registry:

@example
registries = [
  @{
    type = "elpa";
    path = inputs.gnu-elpa.outPath + "/elpa-packages";
    core-src = pkgs.emacs.src;
    auto-sync-only = true;
  @}
  @{
    name = "melpa";
    type = "melpa";
    path = inputs.melpa.outPath + "/recipes";
  @}
  @{
    type = "elpa";
    path = inputs.nongnu.outPath + "/elpa-packages";
  @}
  @{
    name = "gnu";
    type = "archive-contents";
    path = inputs.gnu-elpa-archive.outPath;
    base-url = "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/d12frosted/elpa-mirror/master/gnu/";
  @}
  @{
    name = "emacsmirror";
    type = "gitmodules";
    path = inputs.epkgs.outPath + "/.gitmodules";
  @}
];
@end example

Note: the old argument name @samp{inventories} is still accepted as a deprecated alias and will print a warning at evaluation time. Use @samp{registries} in all new configurations.

@menu
* Supported registries::
* MELPA (pure)::
* ELPA (pure)::
* Emacsmirror (pure)::
* Package archives (impure)::
* Registry entry fields::
@end menu

@node Supported registries
@subsection Supported registries

The following values of @samp{type} are supported:

@itemize
@item
@samp{melpa} — the @samp{recipes/} directory of @uref{https://github.com/melpa/melpa, MELPA} or a fork; contains MELPA-style recipe files.
@item
@samp{elpa} — the @samp{elpa-packages} file of @uref{https://git.savannah.gnu.org/cgit/emacs/elpa.git/, GNU ELPA} or @uref{https://git.savannah.gnu.org/cgit/emacs/nongnu.git/, NonGNU ELPA}.
@item
@samp{archive-contents} — a pre-built package archive as supported by @samp{package.el} (e.g. an @samp{archive-contents} file).  This is an @emph{impure} registry; see below.
@item
@samp{gitmodules} — the @samp{.gitmodules} list of @uref{https://github.com/emacsmirror/epkgs, emacsmirror/epkgs}.
@end itemize

@emph{Impure} registries (@samp{archive-contents}) require Nix to make a network connection.
The user must pass @samp{--impure} when running the lock operation.
All other registry types are @emph{pure}: they are tracked as Nix flake inputs and locked to particular revisions.

Once all packages in a configuration are locked, the user can build the configuration without @samp{--impure}, which means the entire configuration is pure.
Every time the user adds a new package, the lock operation must be re-run.

@node MELPA (pure)
@subsection MELPA (pure)

Use a flake input pointing to the MELPA repository (or a fork) with @samp{flake = false}, then reference its @samp{recipes/} directory:

@example
# In flake inputs:
melpa = @{
  url = "github:melpa/melpa";
  flake = false;
@};

# In registries:
@{
  name = "melpa";
  type = "melpa";
  path = inputs.melpa.outPath + "/recipes";
@}
@end example

@node ELPA (pure)
@subsection ELPA (pure)

Use a flake input pointing to the GNU ELPA or NonGNU ELPA repository, then reference the @samp{elpa-packages} file.
For GNU ELPA, you should also supply @samp{core-src} (the Emacs source tree) so that Core ELPA packages can be built from source, and set @samp{auto-sync-only = true} to skip packages that cannot be built from source:

@example
# Recommended configuration for GNU ELPA:
@{
  type = "elpa";
  path = inputs.gnu-elpa.outPath + "/elpa-packages";
  core-src = pkgs.emacs.src;
  auto-sync-only = true;
@}

# NonGNU ELPA (no core-src needed):
@{
  type = "elpa";
  path = inputs.nongnu.outPath + "/elpa-packages";
@}
@end example

@node Emacsmirror (pure)
@subsection Emacsmirror (pure)

Emacsmirror tracks almost every Emacs Lisp package ever published.
Use its @samp{.gitmodules} file:

@example
# In flake inputs:
epkgs = @{
  url = "github:emacsmirror/epkgs";
  flake = false;
@};

# In registries:
@{
  name = "emacsmirror";
  type = "gitmodules";
  path = inputs.epkgs.outPath + "/.gitmodules";
@}
@end example

@node Package archives (impure)
@subsection Package archives (impure)

An @samp{archive-contents} registry points to a pre-built archive.
Because Nix must download the archive-contents file at evaluation time, this requires @samp{--impure}:

@example
@{
  name = "gnu";
  type = "archive-contents";
  path = inputs.gnu-elpa-archive.outPath;
  base-url = "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/d12frosted/elpa-mirror/master/gnu/";
@}
@end example

Using a mirror (as in the example above) avoids relying on the live GNU ELPA server.

@node Registry entry fields
@subsection Registry entry fields

@multitable {aaaaaaaaaaaaaaaa} {aaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaa} {aaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaa}
