@node Basic workflow
@section Basic workflow

The basic development loop is:

@enumerate
@item
Add or modify @samp{use-package} (or @samp{setup.el}) forms in your @samp{init.el}.
@item
Run @samp{nix run .#lock} to regenerate the lock files for any new packages.
@item
Run @samp{nix build .#emacs} (or @samp{nix build .#default}) to build the configuration.
@item
Run @samp{nix run .#update} periodically to pull in new versions from ELPA archives.
@end enumerate

@node Working around sources
@section Working around sources

If a package's upstream source is temporarily unavailable or you need to override it, use @samp{inputOverrides}.
For example, to use a GitHub mirror of a package whose canonical host is unreliable:

@example
inputOverrides = @{
  tramp = _: _: @{
    origin = @{
      type = "github";
      owner = "emacs-straight";
      repo = "tramp";
      ref = "master";
    @};
  @};
@};
@end example

To remove build-time files that would otherwise cause build failures:

@example
inputOverrides = @{
  bbdb = _: super: @{
    files = builtins.removeAttrs super.files [
      "bbdb-notmuch.el"
      "bbdb-vm.el"
      "bbdb-vm-aux.el"
    ];
  @};
@};
@end example

@node Custom build processes
@section Custom build processes

Individual package builds can be customised through @samp{inputOverrides} by overriding attributes in the package's attribute set.
Refer to the package build derivation in @samp{pkgs/emacs/build/} for available attributes.

@node Checking the versions of packages
@section Checking the versions of packages

@samp{depsCheck} attribute is a derivation that checks version boundaries between Emacs Lisp packages.
If any of the dependencies are lower than the versions specified in the @samp{Package-Requires} header of their dependants, it will exit with non-zero:

@example
nix build .#emacs.depsCheck --print-build-logs
@end example

You can add it to the @samp{checks} output of your flake:

@example
@{
  outputs = inputs:
    let
      emacs = twist.lib.makeEnv @{ ... @};
    in @{
      checks.x86_64-linux.elisp-versions = emacs.depsCheck;
    @};
@}
@end example

@node Troubleshooting
@chapter Troubleshooting

This section describes how to deal with common errors in building configurations.

@menu
* Package not found after editing init.el: Package not found after editing initel. 
* Rate-limited by GitHub::
* Build failure on a specific package::
@end menu

@node Package not found after editing initel
@section Package not found after editing init.el

If Twist cannot find a package you just added, run the lock command to update the lock files:

@example
nix run .#lock
@end example

Every new package must be locked before it can be built in pure mode.

@node Rate-limited by GitHub
@section Rate-limited by GitHub

See @ref{Add an access token to GitHub} above for instructions on adding a GitHub access token to @samp{nix.conf}.

@node Build failure on a specific package
@section Build failure on a specific package

Use @samp{nix eval} to inspect the package metadata:

@example
nix eval .#emacs.packageInputs.<package-name>
@end example

You can also check reverse dependencies:

@example
nix eval .#emacs.revDeps.<package-name>
@end example

