@node --dry-run is your friend
@section --dry-run is your friend

To quickly examine sanity of your configuration, a recommended way is to build the configuration with @samp{--dry-run} flag:

@example
nix build .#emacs --dry-run
@end example

If the command fails with non-zero exit code, it is likely that there is something wrong with your configuration, not an individual Emacs Lisp package.

@node Prefer building from sources
@section Prefer building from sources

It is recommended to build a package from an upstream whenever possible.

This is because an archive tarball can be deleted from its server when the package creates a new release:

@example
error: unable to download 'https://elpa.gnu.org/packages/vertico-0.18.tar': HTTP error 404 ('Not Found')

       response body:

       <!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML 2.0//EN">
       <html><head>
       <title>404 Not Found</title>
       </head><body>
       <h1>Not Found</h1>
       <p>The requested URL was not found on this server.</p>
       <hr>
       <address>Apache/2.4.51 (Debian) Server at elpa.gnu.org Port 443</address>
       </body></html>
@end example

Use an @samp{elpa} registry entry with @samp{auto-sync-only = true} and fall back to an @samp{archive-contents} mirror for packages that cannot be built from source.

@node Inspecting the package set
@section Inspecting the package set

You can explore the full package metadata without building:

@example
nix eval .#emacs.packageInputs --json | jq .
@end example

