@node use-package-always-ensure option
@section use-package-always-ensure option

@uref{https://github.com/jwiegley/use-package, use-package} provides @samp{use-package-always-ensure} option, which makes @samp{package.el} install packages that have no @samp{:ensure} option set:

@lisp
(require 'use-package-ensure)
(setq use-package-always-ensure t)
@end lisp

Unfortunately, Twist cannot handle this option well at the time of writing.

A better way is to @strong{not} use @samp{use-package-always-ensure} option.
Add @samp{:ensure t} option explicitly to each declaration of a package you want to install.
This way, you can simply pass the init file to Twist and also have a choice of explicitly installing some GNU ELPA Core libraries from the upstream.

@node Emacs Lisp packages that cannot be built with Twist
@section Emacs Lisp packages that cannot be built with Twist

It is known that Twist cannot build the following packages:

@itemize
@item
@samp{pdf-tools}
@end itemize

Twist simply cannot build these packages for some technical reasons.
It would be better for Twist to support all packages on GNU/NonGNU ELPA and MELPA, but it is not the case.

For the latest information, see @uref{https://github.com/emacs-twist/twist.nix/issues, Issues} of Twist.
If you have found any other packages that cannot be built using Twist, please file an issue.

@bye
